<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100638245242113></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100638245242113><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100638245242113>Shrikke's Last Post - for the moment</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100638245242113#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Nov 21st 5:40 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>A small apology.  I expanded the story a little bit and have included the entire Part 15. instead of just the part I added.  <br><br>This is the last of Shrkke for a bit.  I am thinking of a story line for another of my characters, so look for that in the future.<br><br>Again, I can not thank enough those who have supported the story with their comments and encouragement.  And of course...if you have any suggestions, please don't be afraid to post.<br><br>Part 15.<br><br>I could tell many stories about my time in the Test.  Battles fought, hunger, cold, the constant struggle for dominance over our environment and over each other; all of these were part of the two years that I spent as a broodling in the wilds of Kunark.  Did I learn what the Test was meant to teach?  Yes, but it was not until many years later than I understood what I had learned and what the nature of the Test was truly.  The Test, above all things, teaches the lesson of balance.  When to use violence and when to compromise, when to seek your own glory and when to sacrifice for the group, when to fight and when to hide, all these lessons of balance, most races learn once they reach adulthood.  The Iksar learn them long before we ever step outside the influence of our own land, because in reality during the life of an Iksar, the Test never ends.<br><br>Before I opened my eyes, I knew that I had passed the Test.  How you ask?    The feeling of a warm clean blanket over my skin and the mattress under my body gave it away in an instant.  I had been keeping third watch, waiting for the sun to finally come over the mountains, when suddenly; I was back among my people.  I could smell the warm food being cooked by the slaves in the kitchen.  I could hear the footsteps of other Iksars walking the halls.  I waited a long time with my eyes closed, savoring the feeling of safety that I had not felt in the last two years.  I did eventually open my eyes.  I discovered I was in a small room with a fire pit set in the wall.  A small fire was burning giving me enough light to see.   Over a chair sat a tunic I assumed was for me to wear and on the table was a pitcher of water and a washbasin.  I cleaned myself, and then put on the tunic.  I was ready for whatever was next.  I went to open the door, when I noticed something the shadows had hidden from me, my backpack.  All the items that I had called my own during the Test, where there, placed neatly in my bag.  On top was my lightstone.  I had not even noticed it had been removed from my neck.  As I picked it up and held it for a moment, a flood of memories came rushing back to me.  I recalled the excitement of learning that both the belt and the robe that we had looted from the dead Hapzass both were magical in nature.  It was also the first time I had heard the word &#8220;twink&#8221;.  I remember the day when we buried broodmates, Tursbaj and Gluzligz.  Both were casualties of another clutch running through our camp while being chased by a goblin warrior.  I remembered when hunger forced us to raid and drive out another clutch so that food would again become plentiful in our part of the valley.  I remembered Larriz.  He was sleeping soundly when I had last seen him.  Had he been taken out of the valley at the same time I had been removed?  I hoped so.  I hoped to see him again in the near future.<br><br>I put the lightstone away and closed up the backpack.  It was in some ways like putting away my childhood.  I tied the top of the bag and placed it under my bed, only to be taken out and my adventures remembered when life needed a touch of balance. <br><br> I opened the door to the torch-lit corridor to find a Crusader standing guard.  He looked down at me and almost smiled.  &#8220;Are you finally are ready to start training in earnest, broodling?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, Crusader.  I am ready to learn.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Are you sure, broodling?  I would not want to hurry you into the next stage of life prepared for you by the Lord of Fear.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, Crusader.  I am ready to start,&#8221; I stated with just a hint of confusion in my voice.<br><br>&#8220;Well broodling, it has been my experience that most would rather start their new paths on a good foot.  I believe that means that your tunic need to be turned around the correct way.&#8221;  I looked down, and sure enough in my hurry to get out the door; I had put my tunic on backwards.  I quickly slipped it around to face the proper direction.  &#8220;Excellent, broodling.  In another couple of years, you might be able to put on your own shoes.  Come with me.  You have a meeting with Arch Duke Zog.&#8221;  I followed the Crusader down the familiar corridors of the temple.  We walked through the teleport pad to the upper levels.   The Crusader pointed to a ladder attached to the back wall.  &#8220;Climb the ladder, broodling.  At the top, the Arch Duke is waiting for you.  You must hurry.  The Arch Duke does not like being kept waiting.&#8221;<br><br>I climbed the ladder as quickly as I could.  Upon reaching the top, I could see the Arch Duke waiting on a balcony looking over our city.   However, the simple task of getting off the ladder to where I could reach Arch Duke Zog was made suddenly difficult.  The floor of the room was built so that one had to make a difficult jump from the ladder in order to reach it.  I steeled my nerve and made an attempt at jumping for the landing and was rewarded being knocked unconscious by the floor in the room below me.  I repeated this activity for the next two hours, climbing the ladder and jumping to the landing, usually taking damage in the process.  Eventually, I succeeded.  As I pulled my bruised body to the balcony, I hailed the Arch Duke and bowed.  He turned and motioned me to come closer.  As I stepped closer to the Arch Duke Zog, he took me by the shoulder and pulled me next to him where I could look over the city of Cabilis by his side.<br><br>Without taking his eyes from the city he asked me, &#8220;How are you feel, broodling.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Respectfully, Arch Duke, I feel tired and bruised.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Why do you feel tired and bruised?&#8221;<br>&#8220;The climb to meet you was difficult, more difficult, than I thought, Arch Duke.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I know you could see me standing here, broodling.  Why did you not call for help?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know, Arch Duke.  It seemed important that I overcome the obstacle myself.  I believed that somehow the leap from the ladder to the room was a test of whether I was worthy of speaking to you.&#8221;<br><br>Arch Duke Zog nodded slightly.  Then pointing out into Cabilis, he continued, &#8220;Broodling, what do you see out there before you?&#8221;<br><br>I looked out into in the city where Crusaders and Troopers stood guard, where groups of Frogloks under the watchful of eye of the Toilmaster re-build fallen and decayed structures, where the Kloks bought and sold goods from under their tents.  &#8220;I see my home, Arch Duke.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I see my home as well, broodling.  But I also see a people under siege who are battered and bruised from the trials of the past. A once great empire that is now a shadow of it&#8217;s former self.&#8221;  He turned suddenly looked at me, &#8220;And still our enemies seek to destroy us.   Do you know why?&#8221;  I shook my head to indicate I did not.  &#8220;Because, broodling, they fear us.  They fear our dedication to our race and culture.  They fear what each of us is willing to sacrifice in the name of our cause.  The fear what can be accomplished when a people have a clear purpose without distraction.&#8221;  He turned and looked back at the city.  &#8220;Do you know why I had the floor built so far away from the ladder, Shrikke?&#8221; <br><br>I was surprised when he used my name.  &#8220;It is a test.  To see who is worthy to speak to you.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;No, broodling.  It is a reminder to every Shadowknight of Greenmist that the road to the top is often filled with painful challenges and most often those challenges must be taken on by without aid.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;So, if I had asked for help getting off the ladder&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I would have killed you.  You would have not had the spark that a true Knight of the Greenmist needs in order to succeed.  Go now&#8230;learn, fight, and understand.  Become strong and intelligent.  And above all, know that the whole of Norrath is fearful because another Iksar Shadowknight will soon walk the earth.&#8221;<br><br>Part 16.<br><br>The path to becoming a Knight of the Greenmist is long.  Before I was sent out to serve my people, I had spent five years learning at the feet of the guild masters lessons in both blade and spell.  It was on my thirteenth hatching day that I received my Pawn&#8217;s khukri and sent out to the entrance of the city to help guard my people from the creatures that roam the wilds.  <br><br>Today, the Iksar are still re-building our empire and our city.  Today we still have enemies without and within that would happily destroy our race and our way of life.  However, today, they failed to destroy us.  And today, the Iksar grew stronger.<br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
