	   <tr><td colspan=2>I did not have much time to add to the story this week.  For those who are following the story, I am sorry.  I will try to add a little more sometime next week, but with Thanksgiving on the horizon, who can say :-)<br><br>On the issue of Thanksgiving...Everyone is aware of the issues that are going on in the United States.  I think that in the light of the events of Sept. 11th that we all feel a little closer to our families and each other.  I would suggest that you make known to your loved ones how you really feel about them during this season.  Tell them how thankful you are that they are a part of your life, because in the end you never know when you will never again get that chance. <br><br>Again and as always, please don't be afraid to give me comments and suggestions on this contining story.  Writing only gets better when you have critism.<br><br>Part 15.<br><br>I could tell many stories about my time in the Test.  Battles fought, hunger, cold, the constant struggle for dominance over our environment and over each other; all of these were part of the two years that I spent as a broodling in the wilds of Kunark.  Did I learn what the Test was meant to teach?  Yes, but it was not until many years later than I understood what I had learned and what the nature of the Test was truly.  The Test, above all things, teaches the lesson of balance.  When to use violence and when to compromise, when to seek your own glory and when to sacrifice for the group, when to fight and when to hide, all these lessons of balance, most races learn once they reach adulthood.  The Iksar learn them long before we ever step outside the influence of our own land, because in reality during the life of an Iksar, the Test never ends.<br><br>Before I opened my eyes, I knew that I had passed the Test.  How you ask?    The feeling of a warm clean blanket over my skin and the mattress under my body gave it away in an instant.  I had been keeping third watch, waiting for the sun to finally come over the mountains, when suddenly; I was back among my people.  I could smell the warm food being cooked by the slaves in the kitchen.  I could hear the footsteps of other Iksars walking the halls.  I waited a long time with my eyes closed, savoring the feeling of safety that I had not felt in the last two years.  I did eventually open my eyes.  I discovered I was in a small room with a fire pit set in the wall.  A small fire was burning giving me enough light to see.   Over a chair sat a tunic I assumed was for me to wear and on the table was a pitcher of water and a washbasin.  I cleaned myself, and then put on the tunic.  I was ready for whatever was next.  I went to open the door, when I noticed something the shadows had hidden from me, my backpack.  All the items that I had called my own during the Test, where there, placed neatly in my bag.  On top was my lightstone.  I had not even noticed it had been removed from my neck.  As I picked it up and held it for a moment, a flood of memories came rushing back to me.  I recalled the excitement of learning that both the belt and the robe that we had looted from the dead Hapzass both were magical in nature.  It was also the first time I had heard the word &#8220;twink&#8221;.  I remember when we buried broodmates, Tursbaj and Gluzligz, on the same day.  Both were casualties of another clutch running through our camp while being chased by a goblin warrior.  I remembered when hunger forced us to raid and drive out another clutch so that food would again become plentiful in our part of the valley.  I remembered Larriz.  He was sleeping soundly when I had last seen him.  Had he been taken out of the valley at the same time I had been removed?  I hoped so.  I hoped to see him again in the near future.<br><br>I put the lightstone away and closed up the backpack.  It was in some ways like putting away my childhood.  I tied the top of the bag and placed it under my bed, only to be taken out and my adventures remembered when life needed a touch of balance. <br><br> I opened the door to the torch-lit corridor to find a Crusader standing guard.  He looked down at me and almost smiled.  &#8220;Are you finally are ready to start training in earnest, broodling?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, Crusader.  I am ready to learn.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Are you sure, broodling?  I would not want to hurry you into the next stage of life prepared for you by the Lord of Fear.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, Crusader.  I am ready to start,&#8221; I stated with just a hint of confusion in my voice.<br><br>&#8220;Well broodling, it has been my experience that most would rather start their new paths on a good foot.  I believe that means that your tunic need to be turned around the correct way.&#8221;  I looked down, and sure enough in my hurry to get out the door; I had put my tunic on backwards.  I quickly slipped it around to face the proper direction.  &#8220;Excellent, broodling.  In another couple of years, you might be able to put on your own shoes.  Come with me.  You have a meeting with Arch Duke Zog.&#8221;<br><br>Happy Thanksgiving all!!<br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
