<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100535573623452></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100535573623452><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100535573623452>The lastest of Shrikke</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100535573623452#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 9th 8:28 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I don't have time to proof this copy...sorry for the mistakes.  I need to get home or my wife will make it so I will need a rez. in real life.  Have a good weekend all.<br><br>Part 14.<br><br>Chasnic and Zzrantan both disappeared one night about a moon after the scale wolves attacked our camp.  Larriz and I did not see them go to say our farewells.   We assumed the Testmaster had determined they had passed the Test and where ready to start their lives serving the Emperor as the will of Cazic Thule dictated.  I was pleased to find Zzrantan&#8217;s mace, which I had originally found on the body of a dead shaman, leaning up against a tree where he had been standing watch.  It was a good weapon compared to the dagger that I wore on my hip.  I offered Larriz the dagger.  He declined the offer, saying that he would rather depend on the strength of his own hands, then the weakness of steal.  Monks, in my opinion, are an odd bunch.<br><br>We adjusted to the change as best we could, considering there were only two of us left in the clutch.  Battling creatures became, essentially, more of an exercise of avoidance than of confrontation.  The lack of fresh meat made both of us rely more heavily on our foraging skills than we had previously.  Also, the possibility of a raid from another clutch became a more likely event with only the two of us left.<br><br>Luck served Larriz and myself well in the avoidance of succumbing to such a raid and provided us the opportunity to join another clutch.  It was twenty days since Chasnic and Zzrantan had disappeared in the night.  Larriz and I were doing what we did every moment we were not guarding or sleeping.  We were trying to find food for the day.  In coming down the path to our camp with a bag full of roots that we had managed to dig up by the stream, Larriz poked me and pointed down at the trail.  In the dust could clearly see the foot and tail prints of a number of Iksar heading towards our camp.  Larriz and I quickly stepped off the trail and headed quietly towards our camp.  I must admit that Larriz was much better at traveling silently.  It seemed that every time I moved a leaf rustled or a twig snapped.  Larriz on the other hand moved so quietly that at times I would simply lose track of him.  Nevertheless, we arrived at a hill over looking our camp without being noticed and in time to see a group of five Iksars going through our camp.  They seemed upset, probably because no food could be found.  We could hear who seemed to be the leader of the clutch, a smallish Iksar wearing a robe and holding a staff, yelling and pointing at different locations around the camp directing each broodlings to search in places where food may be hidden.  They did not realize that all the food we had was in the bag sitting next to me.<br><br>It was a long time before they gave up their search.  After much discussion they decided that we must have some hidden stash of supplies somewhere and the best way to get those supplies was to capture us.  Larriz and I had decided that we had two choices.  The first, to simply disappear until they left and make due without the bedding and other supplies they would surely steal.  The other choice was to try to convince them to let us join their clutch.  The first option had little short-term risk, but would result in some serious long-term problems.  The second choice was dangerous at the moment, but if successful gave us the protection of a clutch once again.  There is a saying:  Better to fight the dragon you know is at the gate, then to ignore it and be surprised when he returns.  The dragon, in this case, was the leader of this clutch.  <br><br>We watched the other broodling hide themselves around our camp, trying to determine the best way to present ourselves to them.  We noted with some humor that the leader of the clutch had placed himself as far away from where battle was likely to start has he could.  Shaking our heads, Larriz and I sat on the hill above our camp eating the roots we had found discussing possible methods of dealing with this current problem.  In the course of that discussion, we came upon a plan.   And according to the plan, I needed to take hostage the largest broodling in the other clutch.  I did not say it was a good plan.<br><br>I crawled through the underbrush towards where the broodling that Larriz and I had come to the conclusion was most likely the main warrior of the group.  She had placed herself near the path entrance to our camp, I&#8217;m assuming to ambush us and cut off our line of escape once we that entered our camp.  I moved slowly from bush to tree with dagger in hand.  Did I mention that stealth was not one of my greatest strengths?  It took me quite a while to finally get in position where I could easily subdue the broodling when the forest itself betrayed me.  A light breeze ran through the forest just as I was about to place my dagger at the throat of the other broodling.  She turned to watch the leaves rustle and out of the corner of her eye, saw me coming up behind her.  I lunged at her hoping to knock her to the ground before he could get her weapon pointed at me.  I partially succeed.  I did knock her to the ground, but she drew a line of blood from my neck beneath my ear and along the line of jaw in whipping her short sword around.  Luckily, I pinned her arm to her body before she could reverse the blade.  We rolled together in the leaves of the forest, one of us trying to get an opening.  Cazic Thule was with me.  I ended up on top and managed to bring the hilt of the dagger down upon her skull, stunning her for a moment.  Unsure how long she would remain stunned I hit her again.  After the second strike, her body went limp.  I looked up to the forest around me.  I was in danger.  The scuffle had not gone unnoticed by the other broodlings who were quickly coming my direction.<br><br>&#8220;Stop!!  Everyone stop!!&#8221; I yelled.  &#8220;Or she dies.&#8221;  I could see the other broodlings stop with their weapons in hand.  I rolled the unconscious broodling closer to the path and into a more open area.  &#8220;I and another want to join your clutch,&#8221; I said to them.  &#8220;Who leads you?  I would talk to the leader.&#8221;<br><br>A voice came from the brush on the other side of the camp from where I held my hostage.  &#8220;I lead this clutch,&#8221; said the small Iksar in the robe as he stood on a rock to see over the top of the foliage what had transpired.  He made no movement toward where I held my prisoner.  &#8220;I say who belongs and who does not belong.  I am Hapzass.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Hapzass, I and my clutchmate would join your group.  The Testmaster has taken two of our clutch and then left us without others to help.  My clutchmate is wounded in the woods and I now hunt alone.&#8221;  Stopping for a breath, &#8220;I am quick and resourceful as this proves.  I would be able to pull my own weight and my clutchmate would be a great asset when he is mended.  What say you?  Quickly, please.  I do not want to battle this one again.  Do not force me to kill her.&#8221;  I pressed the dagger against the fallen broodlings throat.<br><br>&#8220;Kill her and save me the trouble.  She has failed and I will not tolerate failure in my clutch.  Or do you not have the stomach to kill, pup?&#8221;  Hapzass smiled at me.  &#8220;You are not in the position of strength you thought.  You did not think I was willing to sacrifice one of those within the clutch?  Unfortunate for you.&#8221;  He motioned at the other broodlings, &#8220;Kill them both.&#8221;<br><br>I looked at the broodling who had their weapons drawn.  They looked at me with my dagger against the throat of the fallen Iksar.  One of them turned to Hapzass and spoke, &#8220;He will kill her Hapzass.  We have room for one more.  You are being shortsighted.&#8221;  <br><br>&#8220;Are you questioning me, Gluzligz?&#8221;  Pulling his staff closer to him body.  &#8220;Do you think you can question my authority?  I am leader by right of power.&#8221;  The staff began to glow a little.<br><br>Gluzligz bowed his head and spread his hands.  &#8220;No, Hapzass.  I do not question your right to lead, only your decision in this instance.  We could take this one into the clutch easily.&#8221;<br><br>Hapzass snorted, &#8220;Foolish broodling.  We do not need another with my power&#8230;especially this one.  Shadowknights are pretenders of my art.  Kill them or I will do it myself.&#8221;  The staff he held began to glow brighter.<br><br>How did he know I was bound to the path of the Knights of Fear?  It was a question I did not know the answer to for a very long time.<br><br>Gluzligz turned back to me, &#8220;Please do not kill her.  She is my sister and a good warrior.  We can take you into our clutch.  I&#8217;m sorry we can&#8217;t take you both, but our food supply can only feed six.  You understand?&#8221;<br><br>I looked at Gluzligz and smiled.  &#8220;I understand, Gluzligz.  If your camp can only hold six then six it will be, broodling.&#8221;  I pressed the knife harder against the fallen female&#8217;s throat and Gluzligz&#8217; face went pale.<br><br>Hapzass screamed, &#8220;Shut up, Gluzligz!!  This is my clutch.  I hold the power here.  You will not&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>It was at that moment that Larriz stepped out of bushes behind Hapzass and calmly caved in his skull with my mace.  The leader crumpled to the ground without a sound.  Larriz struck again and yet again to make sure the broodling was dead.  At the sound of metal hitting flesh all three broodlings from the other clutch spun around and watched with open mouths as the life of the leader of their clutch came to an abrupt end.  Larriz stood up from finishing the task and waved at me with a big grin across his face.<br><br>The three broodling spun back towards me, weapons at the ready.  I smiled and stood up, removing my dagger from the throat of the fallen broodling.  &#8220;Gluzligz, you did say only six?  Correct?&#8221;<br><br>Gluzligz looked confused for a moment and then broke into a smile.  &#8220;Yes.  Yes I did.&#8221;<br><br>The other two broodling began to understand the nature of the event and everyone began to relax then Larriz broke the silence with a startled cry.  &#8220;Shrikke, the staff this piece of froglok dug was holding, I went to pick it up and it disappeared out of my hands.&#8221;<br><br>Gluzligz eyes went wide.  He spun around and yelled at Larriz, &#8220;Get everything off his body&#8230;quickly.&#8221;  <br><br>Larriz started looting the corpse as quickly as he could.  He had managed to get the belt and robe off of the dead broodling when suddenly blue lines of power exploded from the corpse with a blinding flash.  There was a bright flash of light and a quiet popping sound.  With that the corpse was gone.  Larriz walked out from behind the bushes rubbing his eyes with one hand and holding the robe and belt of Hapzass over the other.  &#8220;I got these,&#8221; indicating the robe and belt.  &#8220;But what in the name Cazic Thule&#8217;s claws what that?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;It was a gate spell, broodlings.&#8221;  The Testmaster appeared as he walked out of the forest.  &#8220;Someone has gated the corpse of Hapzass out of the valley.  Someone has interfered with the outcome of the test.  Someone will soon be answering to me.&#8221;  He paced around where the corpse had fallen.  &#8220;They break with tradition and the will of the Emperor.  This must not be.&#8221;  He must have been talking to himself for as he spoke he never looked at any of us.  After a few moments more of muttering and swearing, the Testmaster stopped suddenly looked at all of us.  &#8220;Get back to your camp.  Shrikke. Larriz. Gather your belongings and go.  I have no need for you all getting in my way.&#8221;<br><br>We hurried and gathered our bedding and cooking supplies out of our shelter.  We stepped out ready to travel to our new camp in time to witness the Testmaster heal the fallen broodling.   She was confused, but held her tongue until we were out of earshot of the Testmaster.  She then made us stop our travels until we explained fully the events of the day.  Her name was Tursbaj.  After a complete explanation she looked me then Larriz over.  Then turned back to me.  &#8220;If you had said you where going to kill Hapzass, I wouldn&#8217;t have fought so hard.  Let&#8217;s go.  It&#8217;s getting late and we need to find dinner.&#8221;<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
