	   <tr><td colspan=2>Here is the lastest.  I want to send out a special thanks to Mugali and the Honorable tochail for the encouragement.  And although I doubt Verant will ever drop me a line to ask for creative assistance, I am honored that you appriciate my words and this story.<br><br>I hope you enjoy the next installment.  And again, don't be afraid to post your thoughts on how to improve the story :-)  Have a good week all.<br><br>Part 13.<br><br>The Iksar have few holidays.  And unlike most peoples, those holidays we do observe are not in remembrance of the Iksar when we were at our best.  We do not set apart days of celebration to pay tribute to a victorious battle or to the hatching day of a powerful leader or even to the memory of our god.  We chose instead to celebrate our defeats.  The day Emperor Rile&#8217;s fleet was destroyed is a holy day.  The day that our race was chased out of Chardok by our own creations is day that we come together to celebrate.  Why is this you ask?  The reason is simple.  Our past victories have taught our race nothing.  Only in times of defeat has our race become truly wiser.  Only when our weaknesses have been exposed and our deeds have been crushed along with our hopes upon ground have the Iksar grown as a race.  We celebrate these days of failure so that we will not forget our weakness and continue to dedicate ourselves to not repeating our mistakes.<br><br>Our small group survived the next couple of moons with few incidents.  Chasnic and Zzrantan taught Larriz and I how to forage food from our surrounding and to recognize the difference between the creatures we could conquer and those who would certainly end our lives.  They did not do this out of compassion, but out of a need for us to be members that would contribute to the continued welfare of the clutch and eventually whose judgment they could trust in a fight.  We tried not to disappoint them.<br><br>The clutch was not again tested again until one evening when Zzrantan was on watch.  I was awakened by the sharp sound of a stone coming through the open window and ricocheting against the back wall.  Instantly awake and knowing that Zzrantan had thrown the stone to alert us to some danger, I sat up in bed with the three other broodling listening for a hint of danger before running out to meet it.  As I sat on my sleeping mat, a sound could be heard, just on the edge of perception like the cry of a child.  Chasnic must have heard it as well because he quietly swore.<br><br>&#8220;Shrikke, you and Larriz, gather wood.  Now!  We don&#8217;t have much time before the pack gets here.  And try to be quiet.  Maybe they will pass by&#8230;maybe.&#8221;  Larriz and I scrambled out off of our mats and headed out of the hut.  Upon exiting, we saw that Zzrantan was already trying to get a fire started.   Chasnic on the other hand simply came out of the hut, stood in the middle of camp and sniffed the air and listened to the noise that had grown loud enough for me to understand the danger&#8230;scaled wolves.<br><br>Zzrantan spoke to us as he struck iron to flint, trying to get a spark to alight.  &#8220;It is not a mature pack that comes our way, but a litter that has just been chased out of its den, I think.  Fire will keep them at bay, if I can get it started before they reach our camp.&#8221;  Larriz and I hastily moved the wood that we had gathered for the morning to where Zzrantan was desperately trying to give life to a flame that would save our lives.<br><br>Chasnic sniffed the air a couple more times and pulled his weapon from its sheath.  &#8220;Hurry, Zzran.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I know&#8230;I know,&#8221; spoke Zzrantan as he struck the steel to the flint over and over again.  Moments pasted and the yips and barks from the pack could be heard clearly when finally one of the sparks started to produce smoke.  &#8220;Almost there&#8230;just a few more moments.&#8221;  From the smoke the hint of a flame could be seen moving it&#8217;s way through the pieces of bark and pine needles Zzrantan had used for kindling.   We all moved around Zzrantan and around the fire pit with our weapons drawn, facing out into the darkness again, waiting the beasts to show themselves.  I saw the first hint of a true flame glinting off the darting eyes of Chasnic who stood beside me when the first attack came.<br><br>The scaled wolf pup came out of the forest at a full run past me and towards the fire pit.  I turned to block the wolf and protect our small fire when a second beast, following closely behind the first, leapt out of the darkness, blindsided me and knocked me to the ground.  The first wolf avoided the small flame burning within our fire pit and headed back to the darkness of the forest, but not without Chasnic and Larriz landing a couple of glancing blows on the pup.  The second pup did not slow down after knocking me to my back, but continued over the top of my form and directly through the small fire. Scattering it and the rest of the fuel into small bits of glowing wood.  As I tried to get back to my feet, I heard a thud, a snap and a sharp yip as Zzrantan&#8217;s mace found the wolf&#8217;s passing form and broke it&#8217;s spine.   As I looked up and saw the struggling pup trying to get up, I knew that our group was just as damaged and paralyzed as the broken wolf without the fire that now lay in small, scattered flames about the fire pit.<br><br>I stood up with my small dagger in front of me.  At least twenty of the creatures now ringed our small camp.  Growling and short barks could be heard from all around.  &#8220;Chasnic, is it the light or the heat that the wolves fear?&#8221; I asked.<br><br>&#8220;The wolves are night hunters.  They do not like the light a fire shines,&#8221; he replied with a voice tight with fear.<br><br>I dropped my weapon and placed my hands to the crystal hanging around my throat.   I had not practiced with the stone around my neck since I had started the Test.  Would I be able to find the lines of force before the wolves charged in mass.  I heard Chasnic and Zzrantan yell at me, then the sound of the wolves rushing into the camp.  I found the force just as the first wolf landed on my chest, again knocking me to the ground.  As my head hit the dirt the light from the stone burst forth from the stone.  I passed out.<br><br>I know that I was unconscious for half a day.  I awoke with light streaming into our hut with my clutchmates standing around talking about what they would do if I did not wake up.<br><br>I sat up slowly, &#8220;We must have won?&#8221;  They turned to me as one with surprise in their eyes.<br><br>Chasnic almost smiled,  &#8220;We did, although you will have to tell us how, exactly. &#8220;<br><br>I told them about the stone my teacher had given me.  About how she had taught me how with concentration I could make the stone shine.  But, unfortunately, doing so took away all my energy.<br><br>Chasnic slapped me on the side of the head, no so gently.  &#8220;Well don&#8217;t do it again unless you tell us.  It&#8217;s a good thing the wolf pups left; because we were all mostly blind after your little show.  I&#8217;m still seeing spots.&#8221;<br><br>They let me rest for the day until my strength had returned a bit.  We ate well.  Scaled wolf is excellent, if you are hungry enough. <br><br>I sat third watch that night.  As I gazed into the blackness listening for the sound of goblins and lone scale wolves, the Testmaster suddenly appeared in front of me.  &#8220;I&#8217;m very surprised,&#8221; he started, &#8220;that your clutch is still alive.  How did your clutch kill the goblin, Shrikke?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;There was no goblin here, Testmaster.  Our clutch was attacked by a pack of scale wolves last evening.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Scale wolves?  But scale wolves do not use magic, young Shrikke.  If it was not a goblin, then who exactly used magic this last evening?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I did Testmaster.  I was given a&#8230;&#8221;  He stopped me with a wave of his hand.<br><br>&#8220;I do not want to know,&#8221; the Testmaster stated closing his eyes and shaking his head.  &#8220;The use of power is not forbidden in the Test, but it is a rare thing for reasons that you may not be aware of right now.  Have you studied with the Necromancers by any chance?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;No, Testmaster.  Squire Mharkas has been teaching me to meditate since I was two seasons from hatching,&#8221; I said.<br><br>&#8220;Squire Mharkas is foolish, Shrikke.  She puts you and herself in danger, too much danger if you favor my opinion.&#8221;  Looking around the dark forest the Testmaster began to speak words of power and fade away.  &#8220;Good hunting, Shrikke.  I have other problems to deal with tonight.&#8221;  With that, he was gone.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
