<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100474247832793></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100474247832793><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100474247832793>Are you tired of Shrikke yet?</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100474247832793#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 2nd 6:07 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>To those reading this series of posts...my thanks for your encouragement.  I have again put fingers to keyboard (since my boss has left early anyway) and have continued the humble beginnings of our friendly Iksar Shadowknight.<br><br>Please don't be afraid of making comments and suggestions or pointing out issues of lore that maybe be problematic.  Good weekend all.<br><br>Part. 12<br><br>Squire Mharkas did pack enough food for a meal.  I did not eat much of it, my stomach was jittery thinking about what the night could bring, but that did not stop the rest of my clutch from eating a hardy meal.  In between mouthfuls of food each told me a little of their history.  Chasnic was the oldest of broodlings.  His father was a warrior and his mother, a shaman of the Lord of Fear.  He figured that he had maybe two moons until the he had passed the test and returned home.  I asked him what path he would follow, his mother&#8217;s or his father&#8217;s.  He was not sure. <br><br>Zzrantan by his own statement was a warrior.  His mother was a warrior.  His father was a warrior.  His father&#8217;s line had been warriors from the time Emperor Rile had ruled the land.  I believed it.  He was big and strong, but not given to much creative thinking.  This is not saying that all warriors are not creative, but intellect is not necessarily the attribute that warriors tend to cultivate.  <br><br>If it was obvious that Zzrantan&#8217;s path was that of a warrior, it was more apparent that Larriz&#8217;s path was that of a monk.  Slightly smaller than even me, but with movements that where coordinated and flowing, it was apparent that the Court of Pain would have another lethal member of it&#8217;s society, if we survived the night.  Larriz had become a part of the clutch only a fortnight ago, but he had found his place in this group as scout and lookout.<br><br>What would be my role in this small group, I thought?  Only time would tell.<br><br>In the pack, as well as the food, were a couple complete changes of cloths, a blanket, a small shovel for camp hygiene, a pot and my burnout lightstone.  The Squire had attached the lightstone to a leather strap that could be hung around the neck.  I quickly tied the lightstone around my neck, and tucked the stone under my tunic remembering the Squire&#8217;s comment that the stone could be a blessing or a curse in my future.<br><br>The meal was quickly over.  I, along with everyone else, began gathering wood and rocks for the night to come.  My trips back and forth in search for weapons gave me an idea of my surroundings.  Our camp was placed in a slight bend in the stream.  The stream wasn&#8217;t large enough to provide any protection, but someone would have to move fairly quietly not to be noticed coming across it.  Preparations where complete for the evening just as the night became truly dark.  I was informed that usually everyone sits guard once per night, but because of the possible danger, everyone was going to spend the night awake.  Each broodling hidden themselves around the camp looking out into the darkness in a different direction.  I got to watch the stream, being that it was the easiest direction to cover.  So, with the dagger firmly in one hand and a pile of large stones next to me, I started my first night of the Test peering into the darkness of the forest awaiting the coming of chaos.<br><br>I waited a long time.  The nighttime sounds where unfamiliar, but none of the other broodlings seemed to be concerned.  As the night continued, I relaxed.  Maybe my clutch mates where wrong.  Maybe nothing would happen tonight.  I do not remember when I fell asleep, but I do remember hearing Zzrantan&#8217;s crying out the alarm.  I woke up with a start, my hand on my dagger and my heart beating wildly.  I spun in the direction of Zzrantan&#8217;s cry to see a skeletal shape walking into our camp.  The figure walked in a straight line, apparently unaware of the four of us.  Chasnic yelled out for everyone to hold their positions.  The skeleton walked to the fire pit in front of our tent and stopped as if it was warming the flesh it did not anymore possess.  Suddenly the creature turned and headed directly towards Larriz&#8217;s position.  How had it sensed Larriz?  I learned later, that the undead had an uncalculated amount of hatred for the living.  That hatred seems to bestow the undead with an uncanny sense.<br><br>The skeleton moved toward Larriz with speed and purpose and Larriz followed suit, running away from the spectral entity.  I could hear Larriz screaming for help as he wound his way through the trees.  Even with Larriz speed, the skeleton was quickly making up ground on the broodling.  Chasnic and Zzrantan both yelled instructions to the fleeing Larriz.  I heard enough of their instructions to know that they wanted Larriz to get back to camp.  I believe Larriz heard them as well, because moments later he came running into camp, the skeleton on his heels.  The skeleton was about to pummel the small broodling in the middle of camp, when a stone came flying out of the darkness, striking the skeleton on the side of the head.  The skeleton backhanded the running Larriz, sending him flying across the camp, then stopped and turn towards me.  I threw that rock?  Squire Mharkas would not be impressed with me.  It was foolish to have the taunted the creature, when I was the least prepared to deal with it.<br><br>As the skeleton turned towards me and started moving out of the camp in my direction, two forms converged on it.  Zzrantan with my mace in his hand swung an overhand blow that cracked the arm off the skeleton. Chasnic struck a blow to the creature&#8217;s leg that connected, but did not seem to do much damage.  The skeleton forgot about me completely and swung its one remaining arm around in a roundhouse that struck Zzrantan solidly in his ribs.  The broodling sagged under the blow, but did not fall, and again swung his mace.   The mace struck the skeleton again, this time collapsing the ribcage.  And again Chasnic swung his dagger.  This time the leg snapped and the rest of the creature fell to the ground in a heap.   Zzrantan struck the skeleton a couple more time for good measure as Chasnic headed over the still form of Larriz.  Chasnic rolled the Larriz onto his back and shook the fallen broodling.  I heard Larriz moan and Chasnic helped the wounded Larriz onto his feet.  Chasnic then started to explain a couple of tactical concepts to the young Iksar.  The most important of which is that running around in circles makes it impossible for your clutchmates to help you and in the future, if a creature was attacking, that the appropriate course of action was to either stand and fight, or run to where your clutch can help you, then stand still and fight. <br><br>We all went back to our positions, peering into the blackness of the forest. And I did not have any problems staying awake.  Two other skeletons walked past our camp, but not close enough to sense our little group.  All was quiet, when I heard the shouting.  Someone or something was heading our direction.  As it got closer, I could hear it crashing through the undergrowth, yelling at the top of its lungs.  I picked up a rock in one hand, not sure of what was about to happen.  As the creature got closer, I could tell that it was shouting for help in Iksar.  Chasnic heard the shouting as well and told everyone to hold positions.  Out of the brush and splashing through the stream came another broodling.  He had blood flowing over his face from a slash over his eye.  His clothes where ripped and slashed, either from a battle or from his flight through the woods.  I watched as he entered our camp and fell to his knees in exhaustion.  He shouted that he needed help, that a skeleton had destroyed his whole clutch and was chasing him.  Chasnic stepped into the center of the camp and walked over to the young Iksar.  Chasnic asked the broodling to which clutch he had belonged.  The broodling told him, but added that everyone was dead.  Chasnic asked the broodling to describe the skeleton, quickly.  The broodling gave a description of a skeleton well over three arm spans tall, with bones covered in scales.  Chasnic nodded his head and placed his hand on the broodling&#8217;s shoulder.   The broodling looked up with some hope, thinking that he had been saved.  He never saw Chasnic&#8217;s dagger as it entered his chest and punched his heart.  The gleam faded away from the broodlings eyes and Chasnic laid the young Iksar on the ground.<br><br>He told everyone to stay alert, especially for a large skeleton coming towards camp.  And he added that if we heard him yell to run, that we where to run without looking back.  He then left and returned to his own hiding place to again watch the night.<br><br>Eventually, the morning did come and Chasnic told everyone to come out from hiding.  We all looked the worse for wear.  Zzrantan was still favoring his one side a lttle where the skeleton had struck him and the bruise above Larriz eye was nto quite completely healed.  Chasnic and I had not taken any real damage, but where very tired.   Zzrantan moved the corpse of the dead broodling to the edge of the camp and we all sat down around the fire.<br><br>It was a hard night and no one was talkative, but I had to ask the question, &#8220;Why did you kill him, Chasnic?  I thought we where short a member?  Was it just because he was from another clutch?  I don&#8217;t understand.&#8221;<br><br>Chasnic looked at me and almost smiled, &#8220;No, I did not kill him because he was from another clutch.  I would not kill another broodling simply because of where he lived in the valley.&#8221;  He sighed.  &#8220;His clutch had attacked or been attacked by what sounded like a scalebone skeleton.  The creature was too powerful for his clutch to defeat and was definitely too strong for our group to deal with adequately.   That skeleton, if it were following him, would have walked right into our camp and destroyed him and us.  I merely hasten the death that was already assured and lessened the possibility of our own.  We barely survived the decayed skeleton&#8217;s attack.  Anything more powerful and we would have joined the undead in their next walk through the valley.&#8221;<br><br>I nodded in acceptance.  &#8220;Chasnic, I have one other question.  Do you know the location of this broodling&#8217;s clutch?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes.  It is not too far from here,&#8221; stated Chasnic.<br><br>&#8220;Then I&#8217;m guessing that we need to loot what we can off this one and head over to the other camp and see if the skeleton has provided us with some extra supplies before any other clutch relies what has happened.  Correct?&#8221;<br><br>Zzrantan laughed.  &#8220;Exactly.  Welcome to the Test, Shrikke.&#8221;<br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
