<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100319914424084></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100319914424084><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100319914424084>Shrikke's Bio - Part 6.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100319914424084#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 15th 10:25 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The next post about our growing Iksar.  Hope you enjoy.  Thanks again for the praise and please feel free to make suggestions.  Good hunting to all who travel Norrath.<br><br>Part 8.<br><br>No one had to tell me that something was going to happen on the day that I reached my sixth season.  As each of the group I played with reached their sixth season, they simply disappeared.  I was concerned, but not fearful.  What is the worst that could happen?  My suspicions where confirmed when Squire Mharkas unexpectedly walked into my room the night before my sixth hatching day and placed a bundle on my bed.<br><br>&#8220;You will need this tomorrow, hatchling.&#8221;<br><br>"Thank you, Squire.&#8221;  Looking into the eyes of my teacher, &#8220;May I ask why?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Tomorrow you start another stage of development.&#8220;<br><br>"I thank you for the lessons I have learned, Squire.&#8221;  I reached under my bed to a box that contained the lightstone.  I opened the box, thinking that I would return the lightstone to Squire Mharkas.  The lightstone was not in the box.  I looked up at the Squire in confusion.<br><br>Squire Mharkas shrugged her shoulders.  &#8220;I have placed the lightstone in your pack.  I would suggest you keep it hidden or it will be taken from you.  There will come a time when it will be useful to you, I&#8217;m sure.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Again, thank you, Squire.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;It is nothing, hatchling.  In fact, it might well become a curse rather than a blessing.&#8221;  Squire Mharkas stepped closer to me.   &#8220; I will remind you now, as I have said before, do not let anyone know that you have practiced magic up to this point.  The ones that will take over your training do not understand magic or it&#8217;s use and will punish you for even a hint of its power. &#8220;   Squire Mharkas turned to leave my room and stopped at the door.  Without turning around she gave me a final piece of wisdom.  &#8220;Remember hatchling, power is drawn to purpose.  Find your purpose and power will come to you.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I will remember, Squire.&#8221;  I looked at the pack on my bed then back at the Squire.  &#8220;Squire, I have one more question, if you please.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, hatchling?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;What is your purpose and am I part of the power that has been drawn to you?&#8221;<br><br>The Squire almost smiled.  &#8220;When you figure out the first part of that question, you will know the answer to the second, hatchling.  Sleep now.  You will need it.&#8221;<br><br>Part 9.<br><br>Squire Mharkas sat in front of the fire holding a cup of warm mead with a blanket over her legs and tail, thinking about what the future could bring.  The Test of Sufficiency was a foolish tradition in the option of the Squire. A full third of the hatchlings would not survive the test.  &#8220;What a waste of potential,&#8221; she thought.  But traditions must be followed.  Every hatchling must past the Test in order to be admitted to one of the major guilds.  A parent, or caretaker in this case, could choose to have a hatchling skip the test, but the hatchling would then be delegated to a life of menial labor and have no real chance of success.  Even Kloks had to participate in the Test.  The Test was the only way to start climbing the rungs of power that lead to glory.  &#8220;He will succeed&#8230;He must.&#8221;<br><br>In the glow of the fire, feeling the warmth of the bright flames, Squire Mharkas heard the steps of an individual coming towards her front door.  The individual stopped and without knocking opened the door to the squire&#8217;s home.  Wordlessly, the intruder made his way through the house to the hatchling&#8217;s room, quietly opened the hatchling&#8217;s door and moved inside.  There was a cry of surprise from the hatchling, a hollow thud from a bunt object, and a sound of a small body hitting the floor.  This was the tradition, that each candidate would be &#8220;abducted&#8221; from his or her home by a member of the sponsoring guild.  To be taken out to the wilds of Kunark to be tested and the participant&#8217;s worthiness determined by skill, strength and luck.  Luck was always the unknown.<br><br>The Crusader walked into the where the Squire sat with a large bag thrown over his shoulder.  &#8220;This hatchling was not asleep.  Did you not give him the sleeping powder in his evening meal?&#8221;<br><br>Squire Mharkas staring into the fire did not look up at the Crusader.  &#8220;Of course I did, Crusader.  But I did not watch him eat his meal.  Maybe he was not hungry tonight?&#8220;<br><br>&#8220;Maybe you are foolish squire with little to occupy your thoughts except your own housework?&#8221;  the Crusader spat back.<br><br>Squire Mharkas did not move.  The Crusader was much more powerful than her.  A direct confrontation would be pointless.  However, confrontation can come in many forms and is usually is best when not direct.  Mharkas lifted her head from her warm mead to look directly into the eyes of Crusader Cotat.  &#8220;He is my charge until you leave this house, Crusader.  I hope you have not damaged him without my permission?&#8221;<br><br>Crusader Cotat shifted the weight of the bag hanging over his shoulder.  &#8220;The hatchling is not permanently injured, I assure you, Squire.  It was your responsibility to see to it that the transfer was done without incident.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;You are wrong, Crusader Cotat.  It was my job to place the powder in the hatchling food.  It is your responsibility to take the hatchling to the place of testing.  I believe that one of the requirements is that the hatchling must be at full health when he arrives at the testing location.  You have attacked a hatchling under my care without my permission, damaged him before the Test of Sufficiency and then hiss at me how I have not fulfilled my responsibilities?  For the attack alone, Crusader Gikzic could have you stationed in the swamp watching the frogloks for a number of seasons."  Looking back down into her mead, "I will file a complaint tomorrow.&#8221;<br><br>Crusader Cotat eyes glinted in the firelight, &#8220;I had to subdue the hatchling.  He attacked me.  I had to defend myself.  Crusader Gikzic will understand that.&#8221;<br><br>Squire Mharkas slowly shook her head with a look of disappointment on her face. &#8220;True, but I&#8217;m sure your fellow Crusaders would be interested to know how you felt threatened to the point of bearing by an unarmed hatchling. That would make for interesting conversation in the barracks, don&#8217;t you think?&#8221;<br><br>Crusader Cotat knew he was beaten for the moment.  &#8220;My apologies, Squire.  I have misspoken myself tonight.  I will take the hatchling to the testing ground, with your permission.  I am sorry if I have offended you.&#8221;  The apology was spoken by one who knew he had no choice to bend, but would not forget.<br><br>&#8220;You may leave Crusader.  I will talk to the Testmaster in the morning to make sure that the hatchling does not accidentally receive any more damage between here and the field.  I would hate to think that you would so careless in the transport of the hatchling as you where in his abduction.  But what am I to think?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;You may think what you wish, Squire.&#8221;<br><br>Crusader Cotat spun on his heals and left the home, quietly closing the door behind him.  Squire Mharkas went back to watching the fire and drinking her mead.  She would have part of a season until she received her next hatchling&#8230;what to do with the time.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
