<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100223861995993></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100223861995993><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100223861995993>Shrikke's Bio. - Part 4.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100223861995993#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Oct 4th 7:36 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Another longish post and again please don't be afraid of commenting on the story.  I'm always up for new ideas.<br><br>Part 6.<br><br>It was six cycles of the moon before I actually got the lightstone to shine.  As I meditated with Squire Mharkas night after night, I had begun to actually feel the forces around me.  Those forces came from everywhere: from Squire Mharkas, from the stone beneath, from the air, even from my own body.  I could, while concentrating, feel the weak forces emanating from the burnout lightstone in my hand.  All I needed to do was connect the force around me to those coming from the stone.  This night I actually managed to grab a line of power from the object closest to the lightstone, my own hand, and feed it into the lightstone.  There was bright flash that I saw through my eyelids, then blackness.<br><br>I woke up sometime later; feeling as if I had been ran over by a rhino.  Unable to move any of my limbs, I tried to open my eyes and was greeted by the sight of Squire Mharkas standing over me with a disapproving look on her face.<br><br>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know if I should praise you or punish you.&#8221; Shaking her head.  She turned around and left the room leaving me to fade back into sleep.<br><br>I slept for what seemed like a long while.  After a time, I was able to stand up and walk out of my room.  The kitchen was vacant of movement.  It was early morning, before the slaves started breakfast.  I walked through our home without any real intent except to stretch my limbs.  I still felt weak, but I knew I would live.<br><br>I jumped as a voice called to me, &#8220;Hatchling, come here.&#8221;  I walked into Squire Mharkas&#8217; room.<br><br>The Squire was lounging on her sleep mat when I entered, &#8220;I&#8217;m sorry I awoke you, Squire.  I will try to be quieter.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;You did not wake me up.  I have been awake for quiet a while.&#8221;  Looking me up and down. &#8220;How do you feel, Hatchling?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Weak, Squire, and tired, but I feel stronger as well.  Does that make any sense?&#8221;<br><br>Squire Mharkas almost smiled.  &#8220;Yes.  It makes sense.  You touched power.  That is apt to make you feel stronger.   However, you made a mistake.  Do you know what mistake?&#8221;<br><br>I knew that I had done something wrong.  Squire Mharkas used magic and the forces around her everyday without ending up in bed.  I thought about how I had connected the lines of force.  There was no mistake in connecting the forces together or the lightstone would not have glowed.  Maybe I needed to control that connection better.  That was it.  I had connected the lines of force, but had not controlled that connection, draining me of my force.  I explained my thoughts to the Squire, sure that I had come to the correct conclusion.  I was rewarded with a tail slap to the side of the head that made the room spin.  As I tried to recover, another blow hit me, knocking me against a wall.  I was still weak enough that I could not focus on the series of attacks that crashed against my body.  I was dipping in unconsciousness when the beating stopped.  Squire Mharkas picked me up by my tail yelled for a slave.  She handed me off to the slave with some instructions I could not understand in my state of disrepair.<br> <br>Soon I was being carried through the streets of Cabalis thrown over the shoulders of froglok.  We stopped and I was unceremoniously dropped on the ground.  The world rocked for a while as I tried to get my eyes to focus.  I did eventually get control of the swaying in my head, and managed to prop myself up on one elbow.  I looked up to see an army of frogloks scrambling up and down busily working on the latest construction project.  I turned my head the other direction to see the calves of a Taskmaster, standing next to me.  I stood up.  The Taskmaster did not even look at me.  I then turned and bowed.  &#8220;Honored Taskmaster. I believe I am at your service.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, you are.  I have been instructed to teach you a very important lesson, hatchling, about the use of power.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;What lesson is that, if I may ask, Taskmaster?&#8221;<br>His whip snapped before I even saw the moment.  My eyes watered at the strap caught me across the small of the back.  <br><br>&#8220;No. You may not. From this moment you are a slave and until someone tells me different you will continue to be a slave.&#8221;  The whip cracked again, this time across the back of my leg.  &#8220;Get to work slave.&#8221;  I paused to ask a question, but stopped as I looked into the face of the Taskmaster.  &#8220;Slave, I would hate to have to have to kill you for not moving fast enough.&#8221;  My question stuck in my throat.  &#8220;Good. Help that group carry those stones to the builders.  I would suggest moving quickly.&#8221;<br><br>I lived as a slave for the next cycle of the moon. And except for sleeping in a pen by myself, I was treated no different that any of the other slaves. The Taskmaster&#8217;s whip was always ready to help speed up my lagging movements.  Twice I was given beating so serious that I thought I was going to die as a slave.   I remember, over the course of the next month, I learned some of the language of the froglok and thankfully, how to eat without actually tasting the food.  However, I did not have any great insights about the lesson I was being taught.  Until one day&#8230;<br><br>I was doing what I did most days, moving rocks, when a shout came from one the other side of the worksite.   One of the slaves, a very large human with blue tattoos over most of his body, suddenly charged a guard.  The human, catching the guard by surprise, wrapped the guard around the waist with his own arms, pinning the guard&#8217;s hands to his side.  The human, in an unbelievable feat of strength, lifted the guard off his feet and with a quick movement and a sound like a branch breaking, snapped the spine of the guard.  The human, throwing the guard down like a broken doll, looked around to see the other guard running towards him with a short sword drawn.  The human picked up the dead guard&#8217;s whip with one hand and a stone as large as a fist with the other.  As the guard got a few paces away from the human, the human threw the stone at the guard.  The guard was expecting the stone and raised his buckler to deflect the object.  However as the guard raised his buckler, he did not see the human take an impossibly long step towards him.  The guard was very surprised as he lowered the buckler to see the chest of the human directly in his path.  The guard tried to raise his weapon, but the butt of the whip had already come crashing down, caving in the guard&#8217;s skull.  The human looked around and saw no more guards.  In fact, all of us slaves looked around and saw no more guards.  I suddenly did not feel so good.  Yes, I was a slave, but I was Iksar and a young Iksar at that.  If any of these slaves decided to take out their frustration out on someone, the most likely target was I.  Luckily, the slaves where not interested in retribution, they were interested in freedom.  With a roar that made my scales rattle, the human grabbed the guard&#8217;s sword and buckler and lifted them in the air.  All the slaves suddenly had a choice, follow this large human and probably be killed or stay at the worksite and certainly be killed.  They chose to run.  In a croaking, screaming, roaring hoard, the slaves ran out of Cabilis toward the Swamp of No Hope.  I suppose they headed that direction because most of the slaves where frogloks captured within that swamp.  I was told later that all where killed as they tried to escape.  I believe that for the most part.<br> <br>Squire Mharkas found me later all alone at the site moving rocks.  &#8220;When I heard about the uprising, I decided to come down and see how you faired.  Are you well?&#8221;<br><br>I stopped from moving rocks and looked at Squire Mharkas.  &#8220;Yes.  I am fine.  And I have figured out the lesson, Squire.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;You have, slave?  And what lesson would that be?&#8220;<br><br>I looked around the site, &#8220;After the human killed the guards today, I was suddenly aware that there where only two guards.  There were at least fifty slaves.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes.  Continue.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220; Slavery is an exercise in the use of power.  By using other&#8217;s power, you do not deplete your own.  By using the workforce of the other races around us, the Iksar can use it&#8217;s own power for other more productive pursuits.  I made the mistake of using the force from myself to power the lightstone instead of using the other forces around me, thereby making myself weak and vulnerable to the beating you gave me.&#8221;  I looked into the face of Squire Mharkas knowing I had come up with the correct answer.<br><br>She did not say anything.  She reached out and took my hand.  &#8220;Time you go home, hatchling.  You need a bath.&#8221;<br><br>I slept well that night.  The first time I slept well in what seemed a very long time.   However, that lesson changed the way I looked at my life.  Squire Mharkas would not find me as open to suggestion as before.  She would also find that I would never again be placed in a position of weakness easily.<br><br>Part 7.<br><br>&#8220;Squire Mharkas, are you my mother?&#8221;<br><br>Squire Mharkas purposefully put down the scroll she was reading and turned to me standing in the door of her study.  &#8220;Why do you ask, hatchling?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;One of the other hatchlings was taking about how he had hatched with his siblings in the home of his parents.  I remember hatching to your face.  You have never said you where my mother, but I thought it might be the case.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;No.  I am not your mother.&#8220;<br><br>&#8220;May I ask who is my mother and father, Squire?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;No.  I will tell you someday, but today is not that day, hatchling.  Now leave me, I have studies to perform.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Yes, Squire.  Thank you.&#8221;<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
