<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100127298554123></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100127298554123><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100127298554123>Shrikkes' Bio - Part 2.</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100127298554123#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Sep 23rd 3:23 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I don't know if anyone is reading this, but posting the story motivates me to write a little more.  I hope you enjoy.<br><br>Part 2.<br><br>Good and Evil&#8230;Light and Dark&#8230;Moral and Immoral.  The whole of Norrath wraps themselves in the cloak of one or the other, trying to define themselves and the world around them.  The Iksar is not interested in such concepts.  Ask an Iksar if an act is good or evil, they will not be able to answer.  One beings act of savagery, is another&#8217;s act of conscience.  However, ask an Iksar if an act will promote or lose a cause.  That question, he can answer.   An Iksar is not defined by morality or lack thereof or even by a chosen cause.  It the skill and efficiency in achieving the goals of that cause that an Iksar is judged by this people and himself.<br> <br>The first two years of my life where spent as most children&#8217;s.  Learning the language of my race, testing my physical abilities and being taught lessons in obedience.  Squire Mharkas was my earliest teacher.  Her duties required her to make sure that I had enough to eat and place to sleep and most importantly, that I understood the principle of cause and effect.  At the earliest age and Iksar realizes that actions have consequences and that those consequences are often long lasting.   Sometime after my second year Squire Mharkas made it clear to me that I was to use the small pot in the corner of the room to relieve myself.  Making a mess anywhere else within room would be unacceptable.  Soon thereafter, I did have an accident while sleeping.  In the morning, Squire Mharkas saw the mess I had made.  She did not say a word to me.  She quietly told our halfling slave to remove the bedding and went about her daily duties.  As the evening approached and I was instructed to rest, I went to my room to find that no clean bedding had been brought back.  I did not ask Squire Mharkas about the lack of bedding, it would have been a waste of time on my part.  This was the consequence to my action.  Was it fair?  No, I was a young hatchling without complete control over my body.  I could not change that fact.  And I had tried my best to follow her directions.  Was I angry?  Yes.  However, consequences are rarely concerned with your ability or intension or even how angry you get.  What I did understand was that it was winter, the stones where cold and it was going to be a very long night.<br><br>As I tried to sleep with my knees against my chest, shivering uncontrollably against the wall of my room, I began to cry.  Are you surprised?  We Iksar can feel and express sadness.  We do not cry as some races do with the shedding of tears, but our expressions are just as heartfelt.  As I whimpered, I looked up to see the halfling slave come into the room.  Hoping that she had not been sent in by Squire Mharkas to quiet me&#8230;disturbing the Squire during here mediation and sleep period was not to be recommended&#8230;I quickly went silent.  The slave walked up to me and gently placed a blanket around my shoulders, patted me on the head and said something in her native tongue I did not understand and walked out of my room.  In retrospect, I know that the blanket was her own.  Actually, that the blanket was the only one she would ever receive as a slave.  I was grateful to her.  The blanket was not as good as my own, but it was warm and I quickly went to sleep.<br><br>The next morning I found the halfling slave&#8217;s body in the corner of the kitchen, with her throat cut.  As I stood looking over the body unable to put in perspective the scene before me, I heard the voice of Squire Mharkas.  &#8220;You may keep the blanket, unless you soil it.  I hope the death of the slave hurts you in a small way, I will not have lessons that I need to teach you be circumvented by anyone.  You have great potential, and it is my duty to see that you meet that potential.&#8221;   Squire Mharkas walked up beside me.  &#8220;Her death is not as important as the lesson you will learn.  My goal is to give you the best chance of successes.&#8221;  Pausing for a moment, she continued, &#8220;If I fail to teach you and you fall from the path set before you because of that failure, both of us will truly envy the death of this slave.  Now, it is time to eat.&#8221;<br><br>Part 3.<br><br>Crusader Gikzic looked up from his study of an ancient tome to watch Squire Mharkas walk into the room.  She was an able student of magic, but not the strongest of fighters.  Her rise to squire had been based mostly due to her ability to teach hatchlings.   To make them not only learn, but understand the lessons they were given.  She had had good success with hatchlings of little or no real potential.  However, her most recent charge was a hatchling with potential that was better than average.  It would be interesting to see how well she did with this one.  Motioning for the Squire Mharkas to join him &#8220;How is your hatchling progressing, Squire?&#8221;<br>	<br>Pulling out a chair across from the Crusader, Squire Mharkas sat down. &#8220;I had to kill my home slave this morning, Crusader.  I will need another.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Take whichever you want, Squire, but how does this answer my question about the hatchling?  You are not trying to change the topic, are you?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;No, Crusader.  I had to kill the slave because she interfered with the hatchling&#8217;s training.  I think the lesson turned out to me more poignant than I could have hoped.  The hatchling is learning lessons quickly. He has a reasonable intellect.  I would like to start him learning the basics of spellcraft, with your permission.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;He is a little young, Squire.  The guild of Necromancers would not accept a hatchling of his age into even the youngest of their study groups.&#8221;<br>	<br>&#8220;I relies that, Crusader.  However, the hatchling is ready.  I am willing to teach him myself.&#8221;<br>	<br>&#8220;That will not go down well with the Necro&#8217;s.  They do not permit the teaching of magic outside of the Guild.  Sons and daughters of scale wolves if you ask me.  Keeping magical power out of the hands of the other guilds.  You know, I once heard of an Iksar studying spells outside of the realm of the Necromancers.  Enchantment, I believe it was called.  I think his brain sits in one of the jars within the Necromancer Guild.  Still alive, if you believe the Elders.  Are you sure you would want put yourself at odds with them?<br>	<br>&#8220;I am willing take that chance, Crusader.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Why?  Why put yourself at risk for a hatchling?&#8221;<br>	<br>&#8220;Because of his potential.  His rise will be greater than mine, in time.  With due respect, maybe greater than yours, Crusader.  I will be pulled up with that rise if I am careful.  I wish to give him, and myself the best chance to make that rise.  The knowledge of magic will be useful to him during the Test of Sufficiency.  Give him an edge over chaos.&#8221;<br>	<br>A silence pasted between the two Knights of Scale. &#8220;I will not give you permission to teach the child, however, I do not forbid it.  You are on your own.  If the Necromancer&#8217;s Guild gets information on this topic, you are alone.  I will not interfere with whatever may happen to you or the hatchling.  Are we in agreement, Squire?<br>	<br>&#8220;Yes, Crusader.  We understand each other.  My thanks to you for your wisdom on this issue.  May I take my leave.  I have much to study today.&#8221;<br><br>Crusader Gikzic turned back to the tomb he had been studying.  &#8220;You may, Squire.&#8221;  Squire Mharkas stood up and headed toward the door she had entered.   Looking up from the book,  &#8220;And Squire.&#8221;  Squire Mharkas stopped with her back to the Crusader.  &#8220;Good luck, Daughter of Rile.&#8221;  <br>	<br>&#8220;Luck has very little to do with it.  I think you taught me that, Crusader.&#8221;  <br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
