<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100102783057853></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100102783057853><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100102783057853>First Post - Shrikke's Bio</a> <a id=fs8 href=/poster.html?user=631&mid=100102783057853#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=20 width=20></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>74 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Sep 20th 7:17 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.60]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Greetings all and welcome to my Tales and Rants.  My main character is an Iksar Shadowknight by the name of Shrikke Hopestealer.  I was in a creative mood one day and wrote up this short introduction to his history.  I hope you all enjoy.<br><br>Part 1.<br><br>&#8220;What is my name,&#8221; you ask.  I could tell you, but you would not hear most of the sounds, let alone be able to pronounce my name properly.  In truth, I doubt my name matters to you.  My race and I are merely the fuel for stories that frightened travelers tell around campfires while the wind howls and the moon is dark.  We have been, until recently, delegated to the role of myth and phantoms of the imagination.  Our existence used to scare children of your kind into eating their meals or quieting before sleep.  Do not misunderstand, we welcome&#8230;nay, embrace the part that we play in the lives of you and your offspring but it is a foolish practice in my opinion.  One day in the future those grown children will have to face the object of their childhood nightmares and in that instant will feel the horror of those stories.  Then, they will die.<br><br>The Iksar is unique among all the creations in Norrath. We alone remember all the events of our life even from the time of our birth.  The memories from the day we are hatched to the moments leading to death are recalled clearly.  In truth, we Iksars even remember some time spent before we hatch, within the egg.   The egg is remembered as a place of quiet security.  Those early moments of life basking in ignorance of the world around are cherished throughout the life of an Iksar but that peace is never repeated.  Whether a blessing or a curse, we can all remember that comfort.  Unfortunately, the warmth of the egg is the last warmth that any Iksar experiences. <br> <br>We also remember the day when the egg can no longer support our continued growth.  It is not lack of space or food that drives a young Iksar out of the security of the egg, but the sudden lack of air.  The place that had, for our entire existence, provided food, comfort and protection, tries to kill us.  All young Iksars initially experience panic.  Some let the panic overcome them and do not survive.  Others move from panic to anger.  That anger leads to the destruction of the place of our conception and forces us into the outside world of contention.  <br><br>Thus, I started my life with the betrayal of the egg.  As I started to feel the air within my egg get heavy, I kicked and punched those walls that contained me.  The more I thrashed about, the more quickly the little remaining air was consumed.  I could feel my lungs burning with the exertion, my consciousness beginning to blur.  At that moment, I knew anger and at that moment I knew freedom.  I broke from my jail, pushing my snout through the newly formed hole and began breathing deeply.  After the first hole, the rest of the egg collapsed quickly.  But unlike others of my kind, I did not start life with my siblings or those who shared their spark with me.  I emerged on a cold black stone, seemingly alone.  <br>	<br>The eyesight of a hatchling is sensitive in the beginning.  My eyes tried to adjust to glow of the dim light.  Suddenly, out of the gloom, a figure moved close to me.  I tried to move away, but my limbs where not yet strong enough.  As the figure moved closer, I could see that it reached towards me.  Thinking again that I had been betrayed, that this enigma was trying to end the life I had so recently fought to claim, I lashed out, biting the figure and tasting for the first time, blood.  A noise came from the shadow as it jerked away.  Again, it came at me.  Reaching for me.  This time I was not quick enough.   The figure grabbed me behind the head and instead of the death I was certain was to come, lifted me up to I could look into her face.   I did not know what she said at the time, it was just sounds.  I know now, because I have said them myself to hatchlings as they emerged into the world.  She said, &#8220;Welcome to your path, brother, Son of Rile, Follower of the Greenmist.  We have been waiting for you.&#8220;<br><br>Epilog 1.<br><br>Squire Mharkas walked through the halls of the Temple with the hatchling wrapped in her arms.  Coming down the opposite direction, Crusader Gikzic passed but turned to look at the Squire.  &#8220;Your hand is damaged, what has happened?&#8221;  Squire Mharkas look at her bleeding hand.  The cut would heal quickly, but was still somewhat painful.  &#8220;This hatchling drew blood when I tried to pick him up, Crusader.&#8221;   Crusader Gikzic bent do look into the eyes of the newest member of the order of Shadowed Knights and received a hiss for his troubles.  &#8220;An excellent beginning, Squire.  An excellent beginning.&#8221;<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
